        <p>The US pressure washing industry is about <strong>$1.2 billion a year</strong> across roughly <strong>32,000 businesses</strong> (<a href="https://www.ibisworld.com/united-states/industry/pressure-washing-services/6538/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IBISWorld</a>), and almost none of those jobs are won nationally. They are won street by street, when a homeowner or property manager pulls out a phone, searches <em>pressure washing near me</em>, scans the top few results, and calls. <strong>76% of people who run a local search on their smartphone visit a related business within a day</strong> (<a href="https://www.thinkwithgoogle.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Think with Google</a>). If you are not in that top group, the job goes to whoever is.</p>

        <p>South Florida is one of the best pressure washing markets in the country, and most local operators are leaving jobs on the table by being invisible in exactly the moment that matters. This guide walks through how to get found locally, why the national marketing terms are a trap, and how Florida's climate turns one-time jobs into recurring revenue. It pairs with our <a href="/pressure-washing/seo/">pressure washing SEO service</a> and the deeper <a href="/pressure-washing/">pressure washing marketing pillar</a>.</p>

